503","after 1435":"after 1435","1436":"1436","1435":"1435","1424":"1424","1434":"1434","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1454":"1454","1531":"1531","ABT 1464":"about 1464","1464":"1464","1431":"1431","1428":"1428","1406":"1406","Cudham, Kent, England":"Cudham, Kent, England","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","Downe, Kent, England":"Downe, Kent, England, United Kingdom","London, England":"London, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Manning","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Cork and Kerry): adopted as an English equivalent of Gaelic <b>Ó Mainnín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Mainnín</i>’, probably an assimilated form of <i>Mainchín</i>, a diminutive of <i>manach</i> ‘monk’. This is the name of a chieftain family in Connacht. It is sometimes pronounced <i>Ó Maingín</i> and Anglicized as   Mangan  .","English: from a Middle English survival of the Old English personal name <i>Manning</i>.","North German and Dutch: habitational name from a farm so named, once in possession of a certain <i>Manno</i> (see   Mann   2) and his kin."],"variants":[{"name":"Mannen","meanings":["Altered form of Irish or English   Manning  ."]},{"name":"Mannion","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Malachy, Brendan, Aislinn, Brigid, Ciaran, Declan, Dermot, Kieran, Liam, Maeve, Siobhan.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mainnín</b> (see   Manning  ).","English and Irish: variant of   Mangan  ."]},{"name":"Mangan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Ciaran, Declan.","Irish: from <b>Ó Maingín</b>, see   Mannion  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Mongáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Mongán</i>’, a byname for someone with a luxuriant head of hair (from <i>mong</i> ‘hair, mane’)."]},{"name":"Mannings","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Donovan, Eamonn, Ronan.","Irish: variant of   Manning   1, with the addition of English excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["equivalent of   Katherine  , also occasionally used in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":31,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Catherine Manning was born from about 1424 to 1434, in England, her father, John Manning, was 35 and her mother, Juliana Brockhill, was 29. She married William Wallys in 1454, in Kent, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1472, in Downe, Kent, England, and was buried in London, England."},"et":{"from about 1424 to 1434–1472":"umbes